Obama becomes the fourth American president to receive the Nobel Peace Prize
The American president Barack Obama will fly into Oslo, Norway for 26 hours to receive the Nobel Peace Prize.
The award will be a diploma, medal and cheque for his exceptional efforts to improve global diplomacy and encourage international cooperation, among other things.
The Head of the White House will be flying into Norway in the morning with his wife Michelle and will have a busy schedule.
First, he will visit the Nobel Institute, where he will have his first meeting with five committee members who have selected him from 172 people and 33 organisations.
The presidential couple then meets with King Harald V and Queen Sonja of Norway.
Then, in the afternoon, the visit will conclude with a grand ceremony, at which Obama will receive the prestigious award.
The fourth American president to receive the prize, and only the third to have received it while in office.
The White House has stated that, when he accepts the prize, Obama will speak about Afghanistan.
The president does not want to skirt around this topic, as he recognizes that he is accepting the prize as a president whose country is currently at war in two countries.
A few days ago he stepped up the war effort by sending more troops to Afghanistan, something that his critics will be stressing.
The ceremony will also include a gold medal, diploma, and a cheque for ten million Swedish kronor (around 24 million Czech crowns).
The donor is planning to give this money to charity, but has not decided on which.
Their busy schedule will then take them to a banquet, which will be attended by the Norwegian king and queen, the ministeral chairman and another 250 invited guests.
Obama has always been reticent about his prize.
The former has reported that he feels that he does not fully deserve it.
The prize is not for him, but for everyone who values the same values.
After hearing about it, he described it as a challenge to take action.
