USA: Repetition is the mother of wisdom
The funny thing is that Obama, known to be the most wise president, is trying to replicate the strategy of his predecessor, having himself considered him to be the most foolish.
When he finally came out with his long-awaited Afghan doctrine, it appeared to have made a carbon copy of Bush's Iraq scenario three years earlier.
The text is not only that he repeatedly uses the words "just like in Iraq", but he even used the name of Bush's declaration from January 2007 as the title of his own declaration: The new way forward.
While three years ago he himself called the idea to send fresh troops to help in the beleaguered civil war in Iraq as "an irresponsible decision with fatal consequences".
The following months showed that Bush's strategy, recommended by his field commanders, was the only possible course of action and so successful that no reports about Iraq are reported.
It did not help Bush's reputation, but in objective terms, it left his successor in a much better position than might be expected.
Obama hopes that, in Afghanistan, the miracle will repeat itself.
The military contingent was again requested by his field commanders, particularly the supreme commander of the Afghan operation General Stanley McChrystal, who even went against the custom of his subordinates to harshly criticize reluctant gunners in the White House.
The commander asked for 40 thousand men to turn the situation around.
The president hesitant for three months, but failed to come up with anything better, and so the general took out of 10 thousand soldiers.
The promise was almost a promise for another 5 thousand, although he was originally counting on 10.
The most difficult aspect of Obama's strategy seems to be his plan to start troops out of Afghanistan within 18 months and to finish the process in three years.
Many doubt that this half-hearted increase will produce the same fruit as the action plan in Iraq.
Although recent internal crisis has been a relatively stable society, its leaders have been adhering to the treaties.
The Afghan situation is exactly the opposite - nobody can be relied on and no treaties are being enforced.
In such conditions, it is difficult for Afghan security forces to prepare, being so used to changing leaders to suit themselves.
Political institutions, no matter how formally they are set up, will be nothing more than a Potemkin village in which patriarchal tribal relations will run wild.
Conflicting interests of a variety of ethnic groups is usually difficult due to the complex relations between them, which is further complicated by the influence of Pakistan and Iran.
Even building an operational state, which is the most basic aim of the operation, seems to be almost impossible.
The time of Obama's strategy is controlled by his voluntarism.
The situation in Afghanistan has continued to worsen and is now on the verge of exploding.
Only a true romantic soul, totally unaffected by reality, could believe that the soldiers sent into the turmoil of this war for an "early return home" will bring any miracles here.
From a political perspective it is pure irresponsibility setting a date for the withdrawal of the troops, as the Taliban will see it as indirect recognition of an American defeat.
The last NATO summit showed that the European people are increasingly willing to participate in Afghanistan operations.
European politicians cannot and are unwilling to explain to voters what the security of Germany or Italy has to do with the Hindu Kush mountains.
Other factors that could radically stir things are what is going on around Iran.
If the situation continues to get worse and increase sanctions against Iran do not have any effect, the United States will face the difficult question of whether to try to resolve the situation with military force or not.
This will be answered when, according to Obama, America orders the victorious withdrawal of its troops from Afghanistan.
Any such solution will certainly mean a dramatic turnaround in the Afghan situation.
The only saving grace for Obama is that there are three more years to the presidential elections, so there is still time to come up with another strategy if this one turns out to be a total whitewash.
