Czech discovery: a substance that works on 'tough' forms of HIV virus
The Czech and German team have been testing a new compound that can slow the spread of HIV virus in the body.
The main advantage of this improved substance is that it also works on viruses which have become immune to medication.
In some cases, this does not offset the fact that the compound used for the normal form of the virus has such a strong effect as some drugs that are available.
No cure has yet been found for AIDS.
Patients' lives can be greatly prolonged by a mix of drugs that prevent the HIV virus from multiplying in the body.
However, they have many side effects.
Moreover, if the virus is not completely suppressed, it can lead to the development of resistant viruses, against which drugs are no longer effective.
The work done by experts from three institutions, Czech Academy of Sciences, VŠCHT Prague, and Heidelberg University, is opening the way to deal with the virus' resistance.
They have shown that substances known as metallacarboranes act on the protein responsible for HIV virus proliferation.
Metallacarboranes are a compound of boron, hydrogen, carbon, and cobalt.
This compounds block the spread of the virus in a different way to all other drugs in use today, and so they may get over the resistance problem.
In their work, the scientists are coming up with new ‘improved’ compounds, prepared using knowledge of the molecular mechanism and its relation to the virus protein.
Metallacarboranes have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-walled cages consisting of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms are connected to a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
The treacherous and harsh virus is a treacherous and hard virus.
HIV protease is the protein of the HIV virus, which is essential to the virus’ lifecycle.
The mature infectious viral corpuscles would not occur if the HIV virus was not split by HIV protease.
If we stop HIV protease, we will also stop the virus from spreading through the patient's body, the scientists explained in a press release published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Czech Academy of Sciences.
In a paper published in the Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, the scientists describe a series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see diagram) are connected by a short organic chain, which is then systematically modified.
Somewhat weaker, but more reliable
The effectiveness of this series of substances against HIV protease has been tested in a test-tube, as well its effectiveness against the more immune(resistant) strain acquired from HIV virus infected patients.
The effect of metallacarboranes on the normal strain of the enzyme is not as strong as that of currently used drugs, but they do not diminish against the resistant strains, whereas currently used drugs are often ineffective.
The unique mechanism of its effect and other properties, such as its biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of other chemical modifications, make metallacarboranes an important compound for future research aimed at suggesting effective drugs against HIV, says Pavlína Řezáčová, head of the Structural Biology laboratory at the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry and the Institute of Molecular Genetics of the Academy of Sciences.
