Management revolution or end of competitive intelligence?
If nothing changes in how France's biggest enterprises are run, our fight for competitive intelligence will have been in vain...
The Management's attitude towards employees reflects the position of enterprises and their consumers before the marketing revolution: employees should be taught to adhere to "values" dictated from above, as it was in the past, when products created by the factory engineers were drop on the consumer.
The marketing revolution moved the strategies for conquering markets again, even if authoritarian temptation to impose products that are unrelated to the consumer’s preferences often resurfaces!
Demobilisation of employees can lead to terminal demoralisation.
Suicides at France Telecom, PSA and Renault are only the visible part of a far more widespread problem affecting management employees.
Demobilisation significantly impacts the development of an organisation's strategic functions, especially in R&D and even more so in competitive intelligence.
In fact, CI "requires from all concerned (...) a proactive approach and long-term vision"; it requires from employees a commitment that is entirely contradicted by authoritarian management methods.
The reason for this is that we are calling for a management revolution, which would consist in placing employees at the centre of an enterprise's concerns alongside consumers.
The very relative usefulness of internal opinion surveys
Does internal opinion surveys - such as those given by Orange to its employees - stimulate this revolution in managerial methods?
However, I fear it will not.
- Firstly, because I have witnessed that, when faced with a new situation, any organisation will arrive, after many detours, at doing chiefly... what it always does!
Next, because authoritarianism - a disease of power - grows proportionally with the magnitude of its own failures.
- Finally, because most leaders have a simplistic view of human behaviour.
The most technical educational institutions have a mechanistic interpretation of psychology.
The latter adopt, for intellectual convenience, the old behaviourist theory, which recently was re-awakened by the "neuro-sciences" of the United States, which have been widely and silently disseminated by business institutes and the Media.
In this way, by suggesting that "levers" can be pulled for management staff's commitment, a recent Ipsos survey published on Figaro.fr promotes leaders into a mechanistic governance position, unsuited to the modern world.
Identify and measure mobilisation factors
In contrast, the management revolution needed for the correct functioning of modern enterprises requires the adoption of a humanistic vision of human behaviour.
It is a combination of a fundamental admission: for employees, commitment to the enterprise is only possible if it is clearly perceived as a way to realize a part of their dreams, ambitions and plans.
Currently, only studies produced through motivation factor analysis adopt the concept of employee motivation.
This study has proved that they form a perceived view of their organisation based on a pre-defined consensus of opinion, which allows them to evaluate what it offers them to achieve their life plans.
By identifying and gauging these mobilisation factors, enterprise leaders can control, predict and anticipate their social performance and turn their resource management "the right way round".
The latter create a favourable terrain for the concerted development of robust and effective competitive intelligence.
