The Party for a Democratic Society (DTP) was dissolved because it was "a hotbed of damaging activities against the State's independence and unfailing unity", the Court President Hasim Kiliç declared to the press at the end of four days of deliberations.
The decision was unanime by the 11 judges, with a majority of seven sufficient to force the disbanding, Mr. Kiliç added, adding that 37 of the party's representatives, including its president, Ahmet Türk, and the deputy, Aysel Tugluk, have been disbanded for five years.
The judge also announced the lifting of the parliamentary immunity, from which both Mr. Türk and Mrs. Tugluk benefited, and the confiscation of party assets by the Treasury.
The DTP has 21 seats in Parliament (out of 550).
The leaders had earlier warned that the representatives would leave Parliament and take their seats as representatives with no affiliation.
