The affected person can no longer distinguish important things from unimportant, the brain can no longer filter out disturbing signals, and the conscious is flooded with impressions.
Like dreams, psychosis also opens the floodgates for a flood of ideas and phantasms, which are coming from deeper levels of the conscious.
The perception of reality in a psychosis is subject-centred, says professor Thomas Fuchs, senior physician at the Clinic for General Psychiatry at the University Clinic of Heidelberg.
Schizophrenic patients are at the heart of events, the meaning of everything is given to him.
At the same time, he is in a passive role, he is, like in a dream, overwhelmed by the events and cannot affect them actively.
Schizophrenic patients often feel threatened, controlled and manipulated.
The reality comparison is often not available to them, the illusions are a brutal reality, awakening is not possible.
To experience a hallucination once in your life
While dreams are often absent, Fuchs says, "the sensual and spatial structure of reality, as perceived during a psychosis, remains intact as a rule".
The delusional thoughts and halucinations are based on reality, the distortion of events occurs within a reality framework.
Precisely why our brain plays such tricks on us is still unclear to scientists.
Special circumstances can cause any person to lose his sense of reality for a short period of time, says Fuchs.
However, not everyone will develop a psychosis.
There seems to be a genetic tendency to schizophrenia, but studies of twins have shown that genes are not the only factor.
Scientists assume that patients have minimal brain damage.
Fuchs says that neuronal maturation of the brain occurs in an early stage of development, through a virus infection in the mother during pregnancy, for example.
It is still a mystery how neuronal disturbances occur, which do not appear for many years initially.
