Support for emergency braking is already obligatory.
Support systems to emergency brakes will have to be mandatory in European cars, as it happened with anti-lock breaks (ABS) and will happen with stability control (ESP).
In fact, they are already in all newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while the rest have a grace period until the end of February 2011.
The measure, imposed by the European Union, aims to increase pedestrian safety, but how they work can also prevent many rear-end collisions.
What the emergency brake assistant does is increase the pressure on the brakes in an emergency, which the system detects through the driver's pressing the pedal.
This does not always keep that pressure through to the end.
According to a study conducted by the car components manufacturer, Bosch, a third of drivers in an accident had not brake before the collision and half of them did not use full force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The intervention of aid requires full braking system, reducing the distance the car needs to stop.
According to an EU study, if all cars were equipped with this feature, 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be prevented in a year.
The reduction will be even bigger - it estimates that one in four accidents would be preventable - when the so-called smart emergency braking systems become popular.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that (via radar or camera) detects obstacles and warns the driver, along with lightly applying the brakes.
If the driver reacts, he helps by increasing the pressure on the pedal if necessary.
If he does not react, and even though the collision is unavoidable, the device uses the maximum force to the brakes to minimise damage.
