New tools for inspection of cars
In these days of floods and accidents, garages are not only making profits.
Every day, thousands of cars that have been in accidents are towed to a garage, where a technician must assess the damage and what the repair will cost.
No claim is the same, and calculating the cost of parts and labor can be a long and complicated task.
Manually calculating the cost of a repair between 20,000 and 30,000 euros, including parts and labor, may take two or three hours.
However, with the help of the most recent computer tools, it would take a few minutes.
This is why almost 100% of technicians are using this system.
Providers of services, claims solutions, and maintenance are working to collect data supplied by manufacturers, and then process it and offer it to customers as a tool.
In Spain, Audatex, of North American Solera Group, is the industry leader;80% of assessments are done using their products.
Other businesses in the sector, competing in data assessment and processing are GtMotive and Eurotax.
Working with data supplied by manufacturers is far from easy.
According to Eduardo Velazquez, the Audatex business manager, 63 manufacturers and importers are working in Spain, and each one sends data in different formats.
The data to process is increasing to the point where they have released more versions, variants and engines in the last five years than in the previous 15.
When a new car hits the market, these companies get to work.
It is very difficult work because you have to catalog every thousand of vehicle parts and enter in your price.
In addition, a "smart" graphic is made for each model, where you can click on different parts of the car.
If it is a mass-market model, the work can be ready in a week, if the process is quick.
If it is an uncommon car, it can take up to three or four months.
The most exclusive models are Porsche, but not Ferrari or Lamborghini.
As for the number of cars in circulation, it is over 99%.
In order to document and develop the databases, Audatex has eight centres spread worldwide (Spain, France, Germany, USA, Brazil, Mexico, China and Japan), each of which specializes in a specific brand.
It has its national headquarters in Alcobendas (Madrid).
There, over a hundred technicians (usually expert mechanics) work with three computer screens at the same time.
Audatex invests 90 million euros a year in developing these databases.
Every month, 2.5 million pieces of information are added, and clients receive updates every two days.
Developing that huge flow of information gives them different applications and different products.
The most common use is maintenance and repair, but depending on the country, there are tools to manage scrap pieces and to calculate the market and residual value of a car.
The only company with used car guide available in Spain is Eurotax.
Audatex does not offer one in our country, but it does in the USA.
The products that Audatex offers, it is easy to get an idea of the kind of support available to professionals in this sector.
The company offers 10 different tools, AudaPlus being the flagship product, is the standard solution for technical assessment.
It includes cars, motorcycles, and light and heavy industrial vehicles.
Beyond the cost of parts, it also includes manufacturer estimates of repair times and paint charts.
This tool charges according to the use, for each appraisal.
The highest cost is 5.75 euros for customers who rarely use it, 10 times a month at most.
Then every insurance company that makes thousands of assessments negotiates their price with Audatex.
Other products such as AudaVIN, allow complete identification of a vehicle and the equipment it left the assembly line with, simply from its vehicle identification number.
AudaGlass focuses on the glass parts of a car, and AudaSubastas is an on-line service for the professional sector that facilitates the bid on vehicles being written off.
Their statistics service is very helpful for identifying trends, geo-demographic analysis and knowing standard deviations of makes and models.
Examples of such models are models that have gone to a shop for damage or how many have been in serious accidents in a particular period.
Gt Motive is the only Spanish company working on such tools.
It sells, among others, the GT Estimate, which is again designed for technicians and provides digital images, access to parts and the official manufacturer's official prices and times.
GT Motive is a Grupo EINSA company, which was founded in 1971 as a provider of automotive services and solutions for assessing damage, malfunctions and maintenance.
The GT Appraisal Guide is its historical reference product on the market.
The team works with 24,000 users in garages, 3,100 technicians and 53 insurance companies.
It has grown by 20% per year over the past three years, and it took in 10.8 million euros in 2008.
Early last year, the globalization process started with the installation of an office in Paris.
Meanwhile, Audatex was founded in Germany in 1966 and opened shop in Spain in 1979.
According to company sources, 62% of its business is produced in Europe and the rest of the world, and the rest of the 37% is produced in North and South America.
Grupo Solera's (Audatex, Sidex, Informex ABZ, Hollander and IMS) global turnover will total 557 million dollars, 3.3% more than 2008.
In our country, the company took in 19.1 million euros, 7.2% more than last year.
In 2005, Solera was valued at 1 billion dollars on the stock exchange, and its shares are now listed for a total of 2.4 billion dollars.
It has been listed on the NYSE since 2007 and is included in the Standard &Poor's reference index.
